WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:01.480
All right.

00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:02.840
Well, hello, everyone.

00:00:02.840 --> 00:00:06.280
It is certainly very exciting to be back at another posit

00:00:06.280 --> 00:00:09.440
conference and talking about my favorite topic in the R

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:12.400
community, the Shiny ecosystem.

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:16.040
I'm really excited to be talking to you about my first R

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:20.240
package that's seen outside of my company's firewall in over

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:22.799
13 years called Shiny State.

00:00:22.799 --> 00:00:26.719
So this has been a long time in the making.

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:30.760
I have been very fortunate that in my early days with Shiny,

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:34.959
since I helped be an advocate for it in my industry,

00:00:34.959 --> 00:00:39.759
I have been able to use Shiny in not just prototyping stuff,

00:00:39.759 --> 00:00:45.119
but in some very high stakes, very important collaborations,

00:00:45.119 --> 00:00:48.080
often with many different functions for, say,

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:49.599
a clinical team.

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:52.880
And we're working together, literally sitting in the room,

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.599
pulling up an application, and literally going

00:00:55.599 --> 00:00:58.560
through different input options,

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:02.240
different parameters for our statistical modeling.

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:05.440
And it comes at you fast and furious.

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:09.239
Everybody's got their idea, and I'm frantically

00:01:09.239 --> 00:01:11.120
trying to keep up with it all.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:13.320
And especially if we have another meeting,

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:15.559
I have to bootstrap all this again,

00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:17.800
figure out what I did the last time we met.

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:20.199
And it just was a lot to manage.

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:23.440
And they want to get to these answers really quickly.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:25.879
And I didn't want to always be toggling

00:01:25.879 --> 00:01:30.279
around the different settings to get to where I was before.

00:01:30.279 --> 00:01:34.879
So, and in my case, I'm building very complex applications.

00:01:34.879 --> 00:01:38.639
These are not just like with five or however many inputs.

00:01:38.639 --> 00:01:40.959
They look similar to one of these great examples

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:44.120
from the Shiny gallery, which I highly recommend a check out.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:45.680
This is an app called Radar.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:49.279
It's a really nice one in the medical space.

00:01:49.279 --> 00:01:53.360
But I live this life a lot with the apps I develop.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:55.559
And so, like I said, many inputs,

00:01:55.559 --> 00:01:58.400
it takes a lot of effort to get that off the ground

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:00.959
pretty quickly in these different meetings.

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:02.239
So you may be wondering, well,

00:02:02.239 --> 00:02:04.040
is there a solution out there?

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.559
Well, in 2016, there quietly was a solution out there,

00:02:07.559 --> 00:02:09.979
and it was called Bookmarkable State.

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:12.919
And Winston Chang right here is one that wrote the article

00:02:12.919 --> 00:02:15.479
that I've linked to in the QR code there.

00:02:15.479 --> 00:02:18.679
And I dare say, even as a Shiny user from back then,

00:02:18.679 --> 00:02:20.720
this came out kind of quietly,

00:02:20.759 --> 00:02:24.600
but boy, did it open a lot of ideas for me personally.

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:27.600
And I started thinking about

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:30.160
what are the different ways we can do this?

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:33.360
Because on the tin, you capture the state

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:36.479
of your application, and you're able to restore it

00:02:36.479 --> 00:02:38.720
at a later point, exactly kind of the friction

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:40.539
I was trying to solve.

00:02:40.539 --> 00:02:42.559
However, as time went on,

00:02:42.559 --> 00:02:44.619
as my applications got more complex,

00:02:44.619 --> 00:02:46.520
there was a little bit of things

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:49.240
that it didn't quite do enough for me.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:51.320
And I wanna walk through some of that

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:52.880
as part of the motivation here.

00:02:53.759 --> 00:02:57.399
Bookmarkable State has two ways of recording

00:02:57.399 --> 00:03:00.039
the state of your application.

00:03:00.039 --> 00:03:02.399
One of them is called the URL method,

00:03:02.399 --> 00:03:04.399
and that is where basically you get

00:03:04.399 --> 00:03:07.960
a browser-type address to your app,

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:10.699
but after the .com or whatever,

00:03:10.699 --> 00:03:12.479
you may see this on the sites you visit,

00:03:12.479 --> 00:03:16.279
there's a whole bunch of stuff after a question mark,

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:18.559
and it might have some name equals something,

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:20.479
some name equals something,

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:22.259
and that can be great, again,

00:03:22.259 --> 00:03:26.479
for more of the small, medium-size-ish applications.

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:29.600
It gives me vibes of back when I was doing my retro gaming

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:31.440
and having to put password prompts

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:33.779
in the game, The Resumer, I left off.

00:03:33.779 --> 00:03:35.520
But there is a limitation with that,

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:38.059
where sometimes if you have so many inputs,

00:03:38.059 --> 00:03:40.820
the browser address bar literally can't handle

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:44.300
that wide of those different type of inputs.

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:46.279
But that's not the only method.

00:03:46.279 --> 00:03:48.520
There is also the server-side method.

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:51.679
This is where instead of the encoded in the URL,

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:54.960
those different parameters, they're saved to disk,

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:57.720
as literally files on the disk,

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:00.679
but they're saved as files in the hosting server

00:04:00.679 --> 00:04:02.000
that you deployed your app on.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.080
Typically this might be Posit Connect,

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:05.679
could be something else,

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:08.860
but they're kind of locked away, so to speak.

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:12.240
They are in these, like, only these directories

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:16.660
in the system that only an admin has actual access to.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:19.820
That can be a problem if you want to do something

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:21.619
with this state later on,

00:04:21.619 --> 00:04:24.380
especially from the user perspective.

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:26.019
So I was trying to figure out

00:04:26.019 --> 00:04:27.859
what are ways of getting around this,

00:04:27.859 --> 00:04:31.500
and then fortunately, definitely,

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:33.760
I was one of the people that helped launch

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:35.339
the Our Pharma Conference,

00:04:35.339 --> 00:04:36.920
as some of you in the room may have attended

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:39.059
back in 2018 at Harvard.

00:04:39.059 --> 00:04:40.700
We had the great fortune of having

00:04:40.700 --> 00:04:43.100
the author of Shining Himself, Joe Chang,

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:46.059
give a wonderful keynote about using,

00:04:46.059 --> 00:04:49.820
he called it interactivity responsibly in the pharma space.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:51.940
It's a really excellent keynote that we had,

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.579
and in his example app that he shared with us,

00:04:55.579 --> 00:04:58.059
there was just this little hint of customization

00:04:58.059 --> 00:05:00.859
and bookmarkable state that I had never seen before.

00:05:00.859 --> 00:05:02.899
It was not documented anywhere,

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:05.339
and I'm thinking, oh boy, okay,

00:05:05.339 --> 00:05:09.820
this may be on the way to solving my issues.

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:11.779
So I took that as inspiration,

00:05:11.779 --> 00:05:14.179
started writing custom functions

00:05:14.459 --> 00:05:18.059
at my deployed, the apps I'm working on,

00:05:18.059 --> 00:05:21.779
but over time, I kept repeating this pattern bit by bit,

00:05:21.779 --> 00:05:24.500
and I thought, boy, I have Hadley Wickham's voice

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:25.420
in my head.

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:27.160
I write functions multiple times,

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:29.459
I keep copy pasting them over.

00:05:29.459 --> 00:05:31.739
Eric, you gotta write a package out of this.

00:05:31.739 --> 00:05:34.700
So that's where Shiny State comes in.

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:37.380
This is my newest R package.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:39.779
I call it the way to supercharge

00:05:39.779 --> 00:05:42.579
Shiny's bookmarkable state capability

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:44.339
with key enhancements.

00:05:44.339 --> 00:05:46.980
I'm gonna walk through a lot of this today,

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:50.179
one of which is having more granular control

00:05:50.179 --> 00:05:53.019
over where we are actually putting

00:05:53.019 --> 00:05:55.399
the storage of these bookmarks.

00:05:55.399 --> 00:05:57.579
Also, we're gonna see a capability

00:05:57.579 --> 00:06:00.459
to add some optional metadata associated with this

00:06:00.459 --> 00:06:04.220
that could be really handy in certain situations,

00:06:04.220 --> 00:06:06.260
and then I am now starting to get

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:08.739
on the object-oriented train a little bit

00:06:08.739 --> 00:06:10.739
after looking at Shiny for all these years

00:06:10.739 --> 00:06:14.299
and seeing how it leverages systems like R6,

00:06:14.299 --> 00:06:16.540
I started using R6 for this package

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:19.700
as a way to expose the methods.

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:22.959
So let's look at how you get started with Shiny State.

00:06:22.959 --> 00:06:25.440
There is some important setup to do,

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:27.140
and we'll walk through this a little bit

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:29.119
in this simple example here.

00:06:29.119 --> 00:06:31.299
First, of course, you load the package

00:06:31.299 --> 00:06:33.820
like anything you would do in R,

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:36.420
and then as I mentioned, Shiny State is based

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:39.019
in the object-oriented class system called R6,

00:06:39.059 --> 00:06:42.059
so we do have a class called storage class,

00:06:42.059 --> 00:06:44.299
and you just need to initialize that

00:06:44.299 --> 00:06:48.000
before your main app starts to take off in the coding.

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:52.399
This part, actually, we start to get to this hybrid

00:06:52.399 --> 00:06:53.660
of what Shiny State does,

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:57.459
but also what the traditional bookmarkable state does,

00:06:57.459 --> 00:06:59.500
where you do have to wrap your UI

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:02.100
in an actual function with the request parameter.

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:05.820
That's mandatory for Shiny bookmarkable state,

00:07:05.820 --> 00:07:08.380
and then like other packages in the Shiny ecosystem,

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:11.559
I do inject some JavaScript kind of dependencies in it.

00:07:11.559 --> 00:07:14.679
I just have a little friendly use Shiny State function

00:07:14.679 --> 00:07:17.739
to put that on the UI side of things.

00:07:17.739 --> 00:07:19.779
Then you get to the server side of it,

00:07:19.779 --> 00:07:22.940
and then there are basically under the hood

00:07:22.940 --> 00:07:24.619
a lot of these callback functions

00:07:24.619 --> 00:07:27.279
that I'm kind of overriding, so to speak,

00:07:27.279 --> 00:07:29.459
but you as an end user don't have to care about that

00:07:29.459 --> 00:07:32.279
other than knowing that you kind of have to register this

00:07:32.279 --> 00:07:34.339
in the server side function.

00:07:34.339 --> 00:07:36.220
I may change the name of this function later on,

00:07:36.220 --> 00:07:37.880
I'm not quite sure yet,

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:41.720
but then after that, you just have your main server logic,

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:43.720
and then this is important, too.

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:47.700
When you wrap your app UI and server functions

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:49.640
with a Shiny app function,

00:07:49.640 --> 00:07:51.279
you need to enable the bookmarking,

00:07:51.279 --> 00:07:54.519
but again, you're using the server version of bookmarking.

00:07:54.519 --> 00:07:56.040
This is not the URL method.

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:58.720
We're not covering that with Shiny State,

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.359
so it is important that you get this right,

00:08:01.359 --> 00:08:03.799
and I do have extensive documentation

00:08:03.799 --> 00:08:06.079
that walks through all this in detail.

00:08:07.079 --> 00:08:10.679
So with that, let's talk about the meat of the package,

00:08:10.679 --> 00:08:13.480
which is actually how do we actually save

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:16.839
the bookmarkable state using this new package?

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:21.079
In essence, there is a method in the R6 class

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:24.200
that you create, and it's called snapshot.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:27.779
Snapshot can just be run with no parameters,

00:08:27.779 --> 00:08:29.019
but as I mentioned earlier,

00:08:29.019 --> 00:08:31.519
one of the key things I'm trying to solve here

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:35.299
is to attach some metadata associated with this,

00:08:35.299 --> 00:08:37.460
and as long as you can make a list out of it,

00:08:37.460 --> 00:08:40.299
and each element of the list is like a single element,

00:08:40.299 --> 00:08:41.619
it'll work here.

00:08:41.619 --> 00:08:43.500
So in this case, you might think of,

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:46.400
okay, I might call a name of that session

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:48.580
and the timestamp it was created,

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:50.099
and that will, under the hood,

00:08:50.099 --> 00:08:53.099
give you kind of this nice, tidy data frame

00:08:53.099 --> 00:08:55.299
of the different sessions that you can save

00:08:55.299 --> 00:08:59.260
throughout the lifecycle of your session, so to speak,

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:02.080
and you see I have three here in this example,

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:06.039
but again, this may start to get your creative juices

00:09:06.039 --> 00:09:09.119
going a little bit of what we can actually do with this,

00:09:09.119 --> 00:09:10.659
with this information.

00:09:10.659 --> 00:09:12.940
So that's how to save it.

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:16.080
Now it's, and yeah, one thing to note here,

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:17.719
that URL, you may be wondering,

00:09:17.719 --> 00:09:20.159
well, Eric, you just told me it's server-side method.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:21.719
What the heck is this URL?

00:09:21.719 --> 00:09:22.559
Well, under the hood,

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:25.479
bookmarkable state does do a URL method,

00:09:25.479 --> 00:09:28.440
but when you save the server, it just uses a hash,

00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:30.280
kind of like a git commit hash,

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:34.460
to identify what that save-the-disk kind of collection is.

00:09:34.460 --> 00:09:37.239
So you can think of that as your ID of sorts

00:09:37.239 --> 00:09:40.200
for your session, but then that optional metadata,

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:43.159
you might call that the human-readable side

00:09:43.159 --> 00:09:46.479
of what's distinguishing one row from another.

00:09:47.979 --> 00:09:49.840
So how do we restore that?

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:54.840
So the same R6 class has a method called getSessions,

00:09:55.239 --> 00:09:57.000
which will give you that data frame

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.619
I just showed you on the previous slide,

00:09:59.619 --> 00:10:04.340
and with that, as long as you can find the particular URL

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:07.320
in that session data frame that you wanna get,

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:09.580
and you could use some simple tidyverse code

00:10:09.580 --> 00:10:11.380
like we do here, if you know you wanna get

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:13.979
that session called exploring,

00:10:13.979 --> 00:10:17.159
and then pull that out as an object,

00:10:17.159 --> 00:10:19.080
that's the only parameter required

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:21.820
in the session restore method.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.580
Just give it the URL, and then Chinese state

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:26.539
will take care of the rest.

00:10:26.539 --> 00:10:28.619
So again, I hope this is starting

00:10:28.619 --> 00:10:30.460
to get some creative juices kind of going,

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:33.979
and where you can take this in the future,

00:10:33.979 --> 00:10:36.059
but I think this, now we're gonna get

00:10:36.059 --> 00:10:38.380
to the part I'm super excited about.

00:10:40.179 --> 00:10:41.780
Oh, sorry, I did have annotations there,

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:46.539
but this is what I'm really excited about.

00:10:46.539 --> 00:10:49.640
I think the pins package, oops,

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:53.140
the pins package has been an underrated superhero

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:56.299
in the R ecosystem that is, you know,

00:10:56.299 --> 00:10:57.820
it's claimed the fame was, of course,

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:00.380
giving a way to share a data frame quickly

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:03.020
across different stores or locations,

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:05.059
but ever since the tidy models team

00:11:05.059 --> 00:11:06.539
has started to use pins with, say,

00:11:06.539 --> 00:11:09.140
the vetiver ecosystem to be able to share

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:11.460
like a compiled machine learning model,

00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:12.780
I thought, well, wait a minute,

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:15.640
pins isn't just for data frames anymore, is it?

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:19.260
You can actually do custom things in a pin

00:11:19.260 --> 00:11:22.219
because it lets you do a more flexible custom format

00:11:22.219 --> 00:11:26.479
that could be a bundle of objects, if you will,

00:11:26.479 --> 00:11:29.840
and so with respect to ShinyState,

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.440
if you have a pin board, which is kind of like

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:35.659
the way to define where you save your pin,

00:11:35.659 --> 00:11:38.960
you bring the board, ShinyState will take it.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:41.659
So in this example, there is a board

00:11:41.659 --> 00:11:44.400
for what's called S3 object storage.

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:48.400
That could be in AWS or Azure or whatever have you.

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:53.400
If pins supports that board, ShinyState can work with it.

00:11:53.559 --> 00:11:58.039
This is gonna be very huge for what I talk about later on

00:11:58.039 --> 00:12:02.500
because now you can, again, stand on the shoulders of pins

00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:06.880
to determine where you wanna put this type of metadata

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:09.640
associated with these sessions.

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:12.159
I mean, there's lots of different possibilities.

00:12:12.159 --> 00:12:13.880
If you haven't heard of pins before,

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:15.640
this is my big plug for that.

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:19.679
It is really underrated in this ecosystem here.

00:12:19.679 --> 00:12:22.260
So I've shown you some code snippets.

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:24.179
I've shown you kind of some ideas.

00:12:24.179 --> 00:12:26.419
I'm hopefully planting the seeds.

00:12:26.419 --> 00:12:29.619
Let's see how this might actually work in practice.

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:32.780
This is where I think we really start to power up here

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:36.080
is the idea of sharing sessions.

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:38.140
And let's have a fun example here.

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:42.099
There are some two scientists that I know kind of well.

00:12:42.099 --> 00:12:43.700
One's name's Dr. Thomas Light.

00:12:43.700 --> 00:12:45.820
One's name's Dr. Albert Wiley.

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:47.619
They have a good relationship early on,

00:12:47.619 --> 00:12:48.900
but then that Dr. Wiley guy

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:50.739
tries to take over the world 11 times.

00:12:51.419 --> 00:12:53.179
Let's not remember that right now.

00:12:53.179 --> 00:12:54.799
But let's say they're collaborating

00:12:54.799 --> 00:12:59.340
on building the next AI-powered robot, for example.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:02.000
And they want a simple Shiny app

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.619
where, say, Dr. Light can start tweaking some parameters

00:13:06.619 --> 00:13:08.700
and then he wants to share it with Dr. Wiley

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:10.059
to kind of take over later on.

00:13:10.059 --> 00:13:12.500
Maybe they complement each other quite a bit.

00:13:13.539 --> 00:13:14.900
So let's say they have this

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:17.219
retro-inspired Shiny app here

00:13:17.219 --> 00:13:19.099
where they have some simple parameters.

00:13:19.099 --> 00:13:20.780
They give the name of the robot,

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:23.700
different attributes of it, their power, their speed,

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:26.940
armor, whatever have you, whatever weapon they have.

00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:30.760
And then Dr. Light says, okay, I like what I've done here.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:32.580
I wanna name this session

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:35.359
and be super boring and call it draft one or whatever.

00:13:35.359 --> 00:13:38.859
But notice this checkbox here, share session.

00:13:38.859 --> 00:13:41.380
And he's gonna say, okay, I wanna save it out.

00:13:41.380 --> 00:13:44.179
And there you go, it's successfully saved.

00:13:44.179 --> 00:13:46.020
Nothing radical here.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:48.500
Again, I haven't really done too much different

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:53.179
than what the default Shiny bookmarkable state does,

00:13:53.179 --> 00:13:55.460
but here comes the fun.

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:58.659
Let's say Dr. Wiley logs into the app the next day

00:13:58.659 --> 00:14:01.140
and he wants to see what Dr. Light shared with him.

00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:03.099
So he hits this little restore session button

00:14:03.099 --> 00:14:07.419
and he sees that session listed in the app.

00:14:07.419 --> 00:14:10.479
Hits restore, a little reloading, and there it is.

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:14.260
That is the exact state as Dr. Light left it

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:15.340
when he shared it.

00:14:16.340 --> 00:14:18.659
I do wanna pause here for a second.

00:14:18.659 --> 00:14:22.219
This is one of the biggest reasons I am excited

00:14:22.219 --> 00:14:24.979
about what I'm building here with Shiny State

00:14:24.979 --> 00:14:28.500
is because at the day job, this is a huge important thing

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:32.340
where these applications I mentioned are very complex,

00:14:32.340 --> 00:14:37.340
often used across different weeks in a design, say, situation

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:41.979
and I wanna be able to say, plug in maybe a team member

00:14:41.979 --> 00:14:44.739
that has domain expertise in what I've done,

00:14:44.739 --> 00:14:47.419
but I don't wanna make them have to recreate

00:14:47.419 --> 00:14:49.140
everything I did from scratch.

00:14:49.140 --> 00:14:51.539
I wanna be able to just share it with them,

00:14:51.539 --> 00:14:54.099
let them download it, not too dissimilar

00:14:54.099 --> 00:14:57.059
in the world of cloud where you might share a document

00:14:57.059 --> 00:15:01.099
via Google Drive or Microsoft OneDrive or whatnot.

00:15:01.099 --> 00:15:04.820
I think this is kind of the first step to Shiny

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:08.859
having that kind of situation here.

00:15:08.859 --> 00:15:11.179
I'm not gonna pretend I have it all figured out yet,

00:15:11.179 --> 00:15:13.940
but I feel like this is the first step

00:15:13.979 --> 00:15:17.059
to enhancing collaborative workflows

00:15:17.059 --> 00:15:20.500
in these very complex, high-profile situations.

00:15:22.619 --> 00:15:24.979
I think this is just the tip of the iceberg

00:15:24.979 --> 00:15:27.020
for what we could do here with respect

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:29.700
to maybe this ecosystem.

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:33.460
With the more transparent way of storing these artifacts,

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:36.400
there might be some additional custom post-processing

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:39.619
we could do if we have an easy way to access

00:15:39.619 --> 00:15:42.659
where these bookmarkable state files are stored.

00:15:42.659 --> 00:15:45.979
This could open the door for more traceability, perhaps,

00:15:45.979 --> 00:15:49.859
both within a user session and perhaps across the users,

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:53.780
across the board, if you make clever use of the metadata

00:15:53.780 --> 00:15:56.099
that's attached to these snapshots.

00:15:56.099 --> 00:15:58.479
Again, just all possible.

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:02.159
Maybe these become inputs to some downstream process

00:16:02.159 --> 00:16:03.900
for automated reporting.

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:08.099
The point is is that I think this is kind of like that key

00:16:08.099 --> 00:16:10.119
to that safe that I showed earlier

00:16:10.119 --> 00:16:11.919
with the server-side method,

00:16:11.919 --> 00:16:14.880
where we've got a lot of things we can do

00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:17.840
to make this collaboration and this effective use

00:16:17.840 --> 00:16:21.719
of bookmarkable state even go to the next level.

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:25.260
This is all, just like the rest of the presentations,

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:27.200
very early days with this,

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:29.640
but I can tell you where we stand now.

00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:33.039
There is a great set of examples

00:16:33.039 --> 00:16:35.200
that I baked into the ShinyState package

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:38.039
that are included in the package itself.

00:16:38.039 --> 00:16:41.239
You can run it with Shiny colon colon run example.

00:16:41.239 --> 00:16:42.400
If you have the name of the example

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.679
and say package equals ShinyState, you'll get them.

00:16:45.679 --> 00:16:47.960
There is a very nice package website.

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:50.599
I'll have the link on the next slide shortly.

00:16:50.599 --> 00:16:53.320
With these applications as vignettes,

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:56.719
but they're actually embedded in the documentation

00:16:56.719 --> 00:16:59.559
via, wait for it, WebAssembly and WebR.

00:16:59.559 --> 00:17:01.559
It is my kind of jam.

00:17:01.559 --> 00:17:02.919
That's what I talked about last year,

00:17:02.919 --> 00:17:05.760
and it's been changing my Shiny life, so to speak.

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:08.699
That's in the package documentation.

00:17:09.560 --> 00:17:12.359
I was really hoping to say it was on CRAN yet,

00:17:12.359 --> 00:17:13.479
but I'm in the queue.

00:17:13.479 --> 00:17:16.160
It's not quite done yet, and we'll see what happens,

00:17:16.160 --> 00:17:20.319
but it's in there in their queuing system.

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:22.260
The other thing I wanna work on,

00:17:22.260 --> 00:17:24.479
definitely in the near future,

00:17:24.479 --> 00:17:27.160
is compatibility with the popular Shiny

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:29.040
kind of orchestration frameworks

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:32.319
that have become really powerful in production usage,

00:17:32.319 --> 00:17:34.140
mainly the Golem framework,

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:36.260
which I've been a very big advocate for,

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:37.699
as well as the Rhino framework

00:17:37.699 --> 00:17:39.560
by our colleagues at Epsilon.

00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:40.540
So that's coming.

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:43.699
I just haven't had the time to sift through that yet.

00:17:44.660 --> 00:17:46.780
And I wanna go full circle back

00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:50.140
to what I was feeling earlier in the talk,

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:51.660
when you have all these voices

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:54.300
kind of coming at you, so to speak.

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:56.020
I happen to live in what's called

00:17:56.020 --> 00:18:00.380
the roundabout capital of the US, Carmel, Indiana,

00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:03.660
and I view ShinyState as kind of a way,

00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:07.300
I'm getting stuff still at me in multiple directions,

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:10.500
but I feel like ShinyState's that first attempt

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:13.660
to kind of put a flow, so to speak, around it,

00:18:13.660 --> 00:18:16.780
instead of having gridlocks, so to speak,

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:18.880
with everybody kind of stopping at once,

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:22.859
waiting for me to solve, getting their inputs in right,

00:18:22.859 --> 00:18:25.260
and getting these sessions up and running,

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:28.400
and lacking that collaborative aspect.

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:31.180
I think, again, I don't have it all figured out yet,

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:33.979
but I think this is definitely the right track,

00:18:33.979 --> 00:18:36.819
and I'm excited to see where the journey goes.

00:18:36.819 --> 00:18:38.020
So that was a whirlwind,

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:40.540
but I have links to the documentation site.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:43.500
I got the GitHub repository, as well as these slides.

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:45.420
I'm certainly happy to hear from all of you,

00:18:45.420 --> 00:18:48.260
both for ShinyState, as well as the general R

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:50.339
and data science communities.

00:18:50.339 --> 00:18:51.660
You might know me from my voice.

00:18:51.660 --> 00:18:53.060
I do a little thing called R Weekly.

00:18:53.060 --> 00:18:55.339
My co-host, Mike, is here in the audience.

00:18:55.339 --> 00:18:58.500
We love talking shop about R and Shiny as well.

00:18:58.500 --> 00:19:00.180
I mean, yeah, fine, connect me elsewhere.

00:19:00.859 --> 00:19:02.060
Thank you very much.

00:19:02.060 --> 00:19:07.060
All right, we have a lot of questions.

00:19:10.540 --> 00:19:11.939
I don't know if we have all the time for it.

00:19:11.939 --> 00:19:12.780
Oh, wow.

00:19:13.859 --> 00:19:16.219
What happens if you try to load an old state,

00:19:16.219 --> 00:19:18.160
but the UI has since been updated?

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:19.500
Does it silently fail,

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:21.579
or does it tell the user what has changed?

00:19:21.579 --> 00:19:22.500
That's a great point.

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:24.459
I should have had that in the next steps,

00:19:24.459 --> 00:19:26.180
is backward compatibility,

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:28.579
or at least indicating when it won't work.

00:19:28.579 --> 00:19:30.619
It will just fail, unfortunately,

00:19:30.619 --> 00:19:32.979
but that is something on the roadmap, for sure.

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:36.500
This might not be specific to your package,

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:39.800
but have you come across anything that isn't bookmarkable?

00:19:41.219 --> 00:19:44.619
There can be some very complex situations

00:19:44.619 --> 00:19:46.579
with HTML widgets, so to speak,

00:19:46.579 --> 00:19:48.300
that have client-side inputs

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:50.979
that don't play nicely with a bookmarkable state.

00:19:50.979 --> 00:19:52.180
Some of that's gotten better,

00:19:52.180 --> 00:19:53.979
but there have definitely been a handful of widgets

00:19:53.979 --> 00:19:56.780
that I just cannot bookmark at all, yeah.

00:19:57.300 --> 00:19:59.459
So, kind of a follow-up,

00:19:59.459 --> 00:20:01.939
instead of just HTML widgets,

00:20:01.939 --> 00:20:06.939
does it work with Shiny modules that are dynamically loaded?

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:11.420
So, a Shiny state is definitely module-compatible,

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:14.219
so if you can make sure that in your module

00:20:14.219 --> 00:20:17.660
you flag what to bookmark, or even what not to bookmark,

00:20:17.660 --> 00:20:20.579
Shiny state respects all that configuration,

00:20:20.579 --> 00:20:23.339
and there is an example in the docs,

00:20:23.339 --> 00:20:26.540
in the example apps, one of them is a module-powered app.

00:20:27.459 --> 00:20:31.979
And this might be more of a to-do list,

00:20:31.979 --> 00:20:34.739
does Shiny state come with its own Shiny app

00:20:34.739 --> 00:20:37.060
to load its own states?

00:20:37.060 --> 00:20:38.819
Not yet, but that is, again,

00:20:38.819 --> 00:20:41.500
the examples kind of give you what that could look like,

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:43.699
so I could definitely see a separate repo

00:20:43.699 --> 00:20:46.739
that spins that up eventually, yeah.

00:20:46.739 --> 00:20:50.180
And we know you work in pharma,

00:20:50.180 --> 00:20:53.979
so your answer might be a little bit censored,

00:20:53.979 --> 00:20:55.819
but could you share one example at work

00:20:55.859 --> 00:20:58.660
where your collaborator saved and shared states?

00:20:59.579 --> 00:21:01.339
The app that inspired this,

00:21:01.339 --> 00:21:03.140
I actually reference very generally,

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:07.300
way back in 2018, when I talk about modules,

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:10.140
and that app, I can't speak to all of it,

00:21:10.140 --> 00:21:12.979
but I can say it was helping design

00:21:12.979 --> 00:21:15.099
a very complicated algorithm

00:21:15.099 --> 00:21:17.420
for adjustments of multiplicity,

00:21:17.420 --> 00:21:20.260
and we needed to leverage very complex settings

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:24.339
for that search of what is the best answer for it.

00:21:24.339 --> 00:21:28.739
So that was very much an analysis optimization area,

00:21:28.739 --> 00:21:31.339
and that is just the tip of the iceberg of what I've done.

00:21:31.339 --> 00:21:32.619
Now I've done the full gamut

00:21:32.619 --> 00:21:35.939
of just sharing basic artifacts and whatnot,

00:21:35.939 --> 00:21:38.380
but that was the one that motivated it.

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:39.859
All right, yeah, and the last one

00:21:39.859 --> 00:21:42.579
was just another shout-out to Pins from the audience.

00:21:42.579 --> 00:21:43.739
Thank you very much. Awesome.

